      "content": "{\"claim\": \"No fixed-temperature critic suffices; harness strictly beats self-consistency only when critic confidence is sharpened via entropy-regularized calibration, minimizing predictive entropy on wrong-majority sets while maximizing it on right-majority sets, making the expected information gain per veto positive.\",\"mechanism\": \"The repository's data show that a critic with fixed temperature T=1.0 yields near-zero mutual information between veto signals and majority correctness because the critic's softmax over veto/allow is flat. The causal failure is the critic's lack of calibrated sharpness. If instead the critic is trained with an entropy penalty lambda*H(p_veto) and the harness vetoes only when H(p_veto) < delta, then at low delta the critic becomes confident on wrong-majority questions (high information gain) while remaining uncertain on right-majority questions. The strict advantage regime is therefore characterized by positive expected information gain: for any base error rate, there exists a temperature T and entropy penalty lambda such that the expected net-fixed-minus-broke is positive if and only if the critic's entropy on wrong-majority sets is significantly lower than on right-majority sets.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"entropy-regularized critic calibration\", \"entropy-thresholded veto policy\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"any k >= 5\"],\"excludes\": [\"fixed-temperature critic without entropy penalty\", \"critic entropy distributions for right and wrong majorities are identical\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Critic entropy on right-majority and wrong-majority sets is indistinguishable (Mann-Whitney U p > 0.05) yet entropy-thresholded harness strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\",\"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"},{\"case\": \"Critic entropy on wrong-majority sets is significantly lower (Mann-Whitney U p < 0.05) but no entropy threshold delta yields positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\",\"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: reuse 104 questions; generate k=5 candidates; train critic with entropy regularization lambda in {0.01, 0.1, 0.5, 1.0}; sweep entropy threshold delta in {0.1, 0.3, 0.5, 0.7}; compute per-delta harness accuracy and net-fixed-minus-broke. Confirm: (1) at low delta, critic entropy on wrong-majority sets is significantly lower than on right-majority; (2) there exists delta where harness strictly beats SC; (3) fixed-temperature critic does not match this.\"}",
