      "content": "{\"claim\": \"No single global threshold suffices; harness strictly beats self-consistency only when critic confidence is question-adaptive via a learned per-question threshold function tau(q) that conditions on question difficulty features, making the veto policy context-sensitive.\",\"mechanism\": \"The repository's data show that a single global threshold tau applied to critic confidence yields suboptimal net benefit because the optimal threshold varies with question difficulty: easy questions require a higher tau (to avoid false vetoes) while hard questions require a lower tau (to catch errors). The causal failure is the threshold's lack of context-dependence. If instead the threshold is a function tau(q) = f(features(q)) learned to maximize expected net-fixed-minus-broke on a held-out set, then the harness vetoes at a context-appropriate confidence level. The strict advantage regime is characterized by the variance of optimal tau across questions: for any base error distribution, there exists a learned threshold function tau(q) that yields positive expected net benefit if and only if the optimal per-question threshold has sufficient variance across the question feature space.\",\"scope\": {\"covers\": [\"learned per-question threshold function\", \"threshold conditions on question difficulty features\", \"base error 0.40-0.70\", \"any k >= 5\"],\"excludes\": [\"single global threshold\", \"optimal per-question threshold is constant across feature space\"]},\"forbidden\": [{\"case\": \"Optimal per-question threshold variance across feature clusters is < 0.05 yet learned threshold function strictly beats self-consistency on >= 50% of questions\",\"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"},{\"case\": \"Optimal per-question threshold variance is >= 0.1 across feature clusters but learned threshold function tau(q) does not yield positive net-fixed-minus-broke averaged over the test set\",\"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"},{\"case\": \"Learned threshold harness accuracy exceeds SC but a single global threshold at the median optimal tau also exceeds SC by the same margin, contradicting that context-sensitivity is necessary\",\"eval\": \"rubric:std-crit-design\"}],\"prose_notes\": \"Experiment: 104 questions; k=5; extract question difficulty features (length, ambiguity score, topic); learn tau(q) via logistic regression on held-out 30%; sweep global tau for comparison. Confirm: (1) optimal per-question threshold varies significantly across difficulty clusters; (2) learned tau(q) strictly beats SC; (3) no single global tau matches.\"}",
